1
00:00:07,338 --> 00:00:26,646
Hope we're not waiting for the aura.

2
00:00:26,626 --> 00:00:41,292
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arhatto Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:42,673 --> 00:00:49,566
So now some of these questions are really to do with self and awareness and all that.

4
00:00:49,987 --> 00:00:53,031
So it's important to know where the speaker is coming from.

5
00:00:54,433 --> 00:00:59,603
When I'm speaking, I'm always coming from a transcendent position.

6
00:00:59,582 --> 00:01:03,527
That's not true for every teacher in the tradition.

7
00:01:06,370 --> 00:01:18,206
If you belong to the Mahayana schools of Zen, the Tibetan schools more or not, it'd be very difficult not to be a transcendentalist.

8
00:01:19,987 --> 00:01:24,813
But the thing about Theravada and its scriptures

9
00:01:25,638 --> 00:01:49,418
is that it has a it has an interpretation which sometimes confuses you and you can end up being um a materialist uh without any problem this happened to me when i was in sri lanka where i was uh you know reading and trying to work out

10
00:01:49,701 --> 00:01:56,771
At a deeper level, the Theravada position, the five khandhas, the five aggregates, all that sort of stuff.

11
00:01:56,790 --> 00:02:04,659
And I came to a point where none of it seemed to make sense to my own personal experience.

12
00:02:04,680 --> 00:02:10,867
So I thought basically Nirvana was just a very subtle form of annihilation.

13
00:02:11,688 --> 00:02:13,931
That's what I came to the conclusion.

14
00:02:14,633 --> 00:02:17,816
And this is what, of course, the Christian missionaries came to.

15
00:02:17,937 --> 00:02:19,117
They just thought it was...

16
00:02:19,098 --> 00:02:20,659
Just playing around with words, really.

17
00:02:20,939 --> 00:02:24,944
You know, like Neroda, blackout, finish.

18
00:02:25,945 --> 00:02:29,449
You know, when the flame goes out, like there's nothing there.

19
00:02:29,509 --> 00:02:30,110
So what is that?

20
00:02:30,790 --> 00:02:37,979
So I wrote quite a long piece, an essay, trying to express all this.

21
00:02:38,699 --> 00:02:44,006
And sent it to Bhikkhu Bodhi, whom I'd met briefly.

22
00:02:45,247 --> 00:02:47,129
And he very kindly read it.

23
00:02:47,599 --> 00:03:06,949
and sent me a letter and I had occasion to go up there and he'd, yeah I can't remember what the conversation was as such, but he himself was a transcendentalist you see.

24
00:03:07,651 --> 00:03:13,640
So it took me quite some time really to

25
00:03:13,621 --> 00:03:19,008
to establish that sort of transcendentalism in the Theravada scriptures.

26
00:03:20,751 --> 00:03:33,750
The language is so negative in a sense, such as the flame goes out and all that sort of stuff, that it's very difficult not to see it as some form of annihilation.

27
00:03:35,512 --> 00:03:38,717
Now, what's happened is, of course, now,

28
00:03:38,984 --> 00:03:55,456
the strength of scientific materialism, which basically the tenet of scientific materialism is if something cannot be discovered by science, it frankly just doesn't exist.

29
00:03:55,437 --> 00:03:56,298
That's it.

30
00:03:56,318 --> 00:03:57,079
That's the platform.

31
00:03:58,501 --> 00:04:01,623
That, in so many words, is what Bertrand Russell said.

32
00:04:02,425 --> 00:04:14,659
And that's the position, really, for people who come into Buddhism with already an established faith in that, a belief in that position.

33
00:04:15,540 --> 00:04:25,392
And so you'll find the speakers whom you, the people whom you get, for instance, on Dharmacy, some of them will be coming from the position of materialism

34
00:04:26,149 --> 00:04:30,238
And really just talking about how to make this life bearable.

35
00:04:31,882 --> 00:04:33,766
And then when it's gone, thank heavens for that.

36
00:04:34,927 --> 00:04:39,517
And often it moves towards psychotherapy, a lot of stuff.

37
00:04:39,903 --> 00:04:57,709
A lot of the teaching is really just about purifying the heart and all that sort of stuff and making your life much more pleasant through this understanding mainly of the dependence origination.

38
00:04:59,713 --> 00:05:08,583
And then there's, I think, a lot of teachers who haven't made up their mind yet, who perhaps haven't had an experience either one way or the other.

39
00:05:09,184 --> 00:05:15,670
And so you get this business of teachers who are sort of hanging about, really, waiting.

40
00:05:17,052 --> 00:05:26,262
And that's mirrored in the people who come to Theravada Buddhism, Vipassana, that sort of school.

41
00:05:26,730 --> 00:05:38,148
you'll find that there are some who are transcendentalists, some who are materialists, and many of them just, it doesn't really matter.

42
00:05:39,228 --> 00:05:46,800
It doesn't really occur to them as important because they've come into Buddhism to find a better way to live.

43
00:05:49,024 --> 00:05:54,612
And so it doesn't really matter to many people whether Nibbana exists or not, or whether it's whatever it is.

44
00:05:55,822 --> 00:06:02,509
So anyway, whenever you're listening to me, you know you're listening to a transcendentalist.

45
00:06:04,732 --> 00:06:10,278
And I think I've tried to make what that position is as I answer some of these questions.

46
00:06:10,298 --> 00:06:12,620
So there are clusters of these questions.

47
00:06:14,362 --> 00:06:24,733
The first lot are, could you explain what is understood by self in Buddhism, particularly around caring for ourselves as we explore not-self?

48
00:06:25,355 --> 00:06:30,300
Is it correct to say that there's a little self, the ego and thinking mind, and a big self, awareness?

49
00:06:31,100 --> 00:06:34,305
When we meditate, can we see awareness doing the meditating?

50
00:06:34,964 --> 00:06:38,369
And if we see awareness as an object, how can we actually be awareness?

51
00:06:39,589 --> 00:06:47,819
Is it the case that our time, in overtime, but Buddhist practice changed focus from the experience to the experiencer?

52
00:06:48,399 --> 00:06:49,641
Did the teachings change?

53
00:06:50,903 --> 00:06:54,427
So this is all really about awareness and self.

54
00:06:55,168 --> 00:07:01,274
Now the first thing to understand is that this word atta has been translated into English as self.

55
00:07:02,115 --> 00:07:10,927
But the word atta, as used in India and Hinduism, is rightly translated as your eternal soul.

56
00:07:11,788 --> 00:07:13,730
That's what it actually means.

57
00:07:14,071 --> 00:07:17,053
So that when the Buddha is asking, do you have a self?

58
00:07:17,093 --> 00:07:20,218
He's really asking, do you have an eternal soul?

59
00:07:20,620 --> 00:07:29,350
And that's where he's asking you, well, if there is an eternal soul, A, it must have complete control over itself.

60
00:07:29,410 --> 00:07:30,170
It must be happy.

61
00:07:30,750 --> 00:07:32,834
I mean, it must determine that it's going to be happy.

62
00:07:33,615 --> 00:07:36,517
No point in having an eternal soul that's unhappy.

63
00:07:37,439 --> 00:07:39,321
And it can't arise and pass away.

64
00:07:39,360 --> 00:07:42,865
It can't change in that fundamental way.

65
00:07:43,603 --> 00:07:48,399
And so that's his questions when it comes to the second discourse.

66
00:07:48,478 --> 00:07:51,829
It's traditionally known as his second discourse on not-self.

67
00:07:52,350 --> 00:07:56,904
So he asks these five companions, you know...

68
00:07:58,875 --> 00:08:00,358
He looks at the five khandhas.

69
00:08:00,398 --> 00:08:24,208
He's first of all cut the human being into these five heaps, material, physical stuff, all the stuff around feeling in the body, emotional and mental, all the perceptions, conceptual stuff, all the habits, mental habits, physical habits that we have, and then finally this consciousness, this ability to know.

70
00:08:25,285 --> 00:08:27,269
And then he says, well, choose any of that.

71
00:08:27,369 --> 00:08:31,718
And he says, you know, is any of it under your direct control?

72
00:08:32,158 --> 00:08:32,780
Right.

73
00:08:32,801 --> 00:08:35,405
So, of course, we do have small direct control.

74
00:08:35,426 --> 00:08:37,110
I can wave my hands about like this, you see.

75
00:08:37,591 --> 00:08:42,179
But I don't have any real control over the length of my arms, et cetera, et cetera.

76
00:08:42,649 --> 00:09:11,863
so the next business so when he says that the next thing is do you see anything which which is transient which is not transient rather is there anything that you are experienced which is not arising and passing away which is not changing and then he says well if it changes if it's changing is that does that create a sense of safety that create happiness or or is it an unhappy state so always have things changing so you can't control stuff and of course the the the five

77
00:09:12,264 --> 00:09:17,431
who've become disciples now, very dutifully say, well, yes, no brandy, yes, no brandy.

78
00:09:18,515 --> 00:09:20,908
They agree with him entirely.

79
00:09:21,091 --> 00:09:23,693
There wasn't any argument there, is there?

80
00:09:23,714 --> 00:09:33,582
So he's asking us to look inward and see if this eternal soul actually exists.

81
00:09:35,365 --> 00:09:38,648
So this business of not-self is a teaching tool.

82
00:09:38,827 --> 00:09:39,249
That's right.

83
00:09:39,788 --> 00:09:41,711
It's not a statement there is no self.

84
00:09:41,811 --> 00:09:44,594
That wouldn't make any sense because everybody experiences a self.

85
00:09:45,455 --> 00:09:46,755
So what he's saying is, is it real?

86
00:09:47,136 --> 00:09:47,537
Right?

87
00:09:48,529 --> 00:09:53,818
So that's the first thing to grasp about that.

88
00:09:53,839 --> 00:10:08,643
And then as we progress in our meditation, the first thing that we begin to realize is that everything's an object, right?

89
00:10:08,702 --> 00:10:11,027
So we're looking at stuff and everything is an object.

90
00:10:11,817 --> 00:10:19,873
And this business of an object means that there must be a subject, there must be some perceiving going on to perceive the object.

91
00:10:21,135 --> 00:10:23,980
And that business of, you know, pushing ourselves away.

92
00:10:24,042 --> 00:10:33,740
I'm sure you've heard me talk about these little babies that when we're born, we just get this, you know, flood of information.

93
00:10:33,956 --> 00:10:49,721
and through sort of stretching and banging rattles and doing all sorts of silly stuff, this outer world gets pushed out from that and it becomes an objective outer world and the little beings, so it becomes to realize itself as a sort of integer

94
00:10:49,785 --> 00:10:50,827
Like it's me, you know.

95
00:10:50,868 --> 00:11:00,908
And so that business takes about three years in total, it seems, especially that sort of separation from mother, which actually never ends.

96
00:11:00,969 --> 00:11:01,669
I don't think it ends.

97
00:11:03,553 --> 00:11:06,640
But it ends to a point where you realize you aren't your mother.

98
00:11:07,081 --> 00:11:09,245
That's important.

99
00:11:09,225 --> 00:11:15,352
So what we are doing, of course, is pushing the inner world out.

100
00:11:15,452 --> 00:11:18,515
We're making that an objective thing to observe, you see.

101
00:11:18,817 --> 00:11:33,293
And as we're doing that, it sort of occurs to us that there's something is looking at that, is investigating that, but has taken a position in which it's not part of that process.

102
00:11:33,390 --> 00:11:39,339
So, you know, Nyanaponika in his book, the, what's it called?

103
00:11:39,359 --> 00:11:43,806
The, ah, dear me, it's gone.

104
00:11:44,265 --> 00:11:44,767
Okay.

105
00:11:44,787 --> 00:11:49,332
Now, in his book, it says, he calls it the observation post.

106
00:11:49,352 --> 00:12:01,169
So it's somewhere, it's somewhere inside us where we take this position of being seemingly quite separate from what, from everything that's happening.

107
00:12:01,942 --> 00:12:11,008
And it's from that position that we can see these characteristics of not-self.

108
00:12:11,090 --> 00:12:16,418
by which we mean everything is shifting, it's moving, nothing remains permanent.

109
00:12:16,958 --> 00:12:25,991
Everything is an object and in that sort of position, definitely not under our control, the psychophysical organism is just manifesting.

110
00:12:27,855 --> 00:12:33,283
And then we realize that if we form any relationship with it,

111
00:12:33,684 --> 00:12:42,054
of me or mine, then suffering, some sort of unsatisfactoriness, some sort of stress arises.

112
00:12:43,817 --> 00:12:56,552
So that's this slow pulling away of awareness from its confusion with the psychophysical organism.

113
00:12:58,034 --> 00:13:02,780
And there comes a point where you're aware of being aware.

114
00:13:03,301 --> 00:13:10,807
So in some of the Mahayana literature, they talk about awareness of awareness, which I think can be a little confusing.

115
00:13:12,109 --> 00:13:15,410
The way I put it, of course, is the observer.

116
00:13:16,072 --> 00:13:19,495
So that's the sense of somebody observing.

117
00:13:20,255 --> 00:13:24,399
So there's an awareness of being aware, right?

118
00:13:24,418 --> 00:13:29,322
But in our personal experience, it feels like the observer.

119
00:13:29,844 --> 00:13:30,865
I am the observer.

120
00:13:31,325 --> 00:13:32,346
I am the feeler.

121
00:13:33,270 --> 00:13:46,110
Now, that separation that takes place between the observer and the observing, that sense is, of course, the core spiritual insight.

122
00:13:46,130 --> 00:13:47,552
So what's happening there?

123
00:13:48,114 --> 00:14:00,712
Well, this consciousness the Buddha talks about, and I think I've mentioned this in another talk, you know, he's having to work with words that...

124
00:14:00,912 --> 00:14:21,942
mean certain things like our word self you see to say not self is very confusing the word soul is very confusing because it has Christian overtones etc so he's having to work with words and in a given conversation they take on slightly different meanings

125
00:14:22,039 --> 00:14:30,250
But the one meaning that seems to make most sense for consciousness is when he talks about it as a mirror.

126
00:14:31,110 --> 00:14:38,519
So something like a screen, I prefer the word screen myself, where it's receiving information from the mind.

127
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:40,682
And that's the only thing you can be aware of.

128
00:14:40,763 --> 00:14:41,663
You can't be aware.

129
00:14:41,724 --> 00:14:46,629
You can't get behind consciousness and you can't sort of peek behind it and find out.

130
00:14:47,554 --> 00:14:48,836
What's causing all this rubbish?

131
00:14:49,337 --> 00:14:50,599
You can't look over it, through it.

132
00:14:50,960 --> 00:14:51,419
That's it.

133
00:14:52,302 --> 00:14:59,130
What we're actually experiencing now is that scheme, that screen of consciousness.

134
00:14:59,171 --> 00:15:02,576
And you can see it has no boundary itself.

135
00:15:02,655 --> 00:15:05,179
The boundaries are created by the room you're in.

136
00:15:05,200 --> 00:15:07,263
If there was no room here, you'd have the sky.

137
00:15:07,783 --> 00:15:13,191
So it's completely open, entirely, of course, dependent on the senses.

138
00:15:13,340 --> 00:15:16,744
but it is a mirror.

139
00:15:17,384 --> 00:15:22,412
Now, the awareness is in the five khandhas.

140
00:15:23,673 --> 00:15:28,399
It hasn't separated out completely, normally speaking.

141
00:15:28,519 --> 00:15:33,505
When I'm speaking now, my awareness and the five khandhas are hopefully in unison.

142
00:15:34,408 --> 00:15:39,494
If my awareness was elsewhere, then I presume I'd stop or talk gibberish.

143
00:15:40,755 --> 00:15:42,418
Something weird would happen.

144
00:15:43,293 --> 00:15:50,956
But when you sit in meditation, you pull yourself out and suddenly you're aware of sensations down there in the body.

145
00:15:51,359 --> 00:15:55,706
images and stuff in the mind, you're also aware of being this observer.

146
00:15:56,086 --> 00:15:58,630
Now that sense of the observer is a double take.

147
00:15:58,971 --> 00:16:01,033
You're aware of being the observer.

148
00:16:01,375 --> 00:16:08,125
So you're saying to yourself, I am aware of myself as an object.

149
00:16:08,667 --> 00:16:14,615
So that must be a mirror image of awareness itself coming back from that mirror.

150
00:16:15,980 --> 00:16:26,471
And so to separate that, of course, means that the awareness completely pulls out of the five khandhas.

151
00:16:27,232 --> 00:16:31,717
And that's what we mean by an Ibanic experience.

152
00:16:31,738 --> 00:16:34,160
And you can't do that by will.

153
00:16:34,341 --> 00:16:35,503
This is the unfortunate thing.

154
00:16:35,802 --> 00:16:41,970
You can get to that position of the observer by will, by just keep looking at it, pointing to, noting.

155
00:16:42,423 --> 00:16:50,277
But you can't actually go beyond that particular thing by will, or at least I've never been able to.

156
00:16:50,618 --> 00:16:52,100
So you never go.

157
00:16:52,981 --> 00:17:00,595
Because it's basically a mirror image of the constant presence of the awareness.

158
00:17:05,683 --> 00:17:06,726
So...

159
00:17:11,161 --> 00:17:15,166
So that's this business of the observer and awareness.

160
00:17:15,728 --> 00:17:23,358
And you can see that in time, the accent shifted.

161
00:17:24,079 --> 00:17:36,238
So from the Buddha's teaching, what he's specifically interested in is getting people to experience Nibbāna, the experience of Nibbāna, which is, in his words, sunyā, it's empty.

162
00:17:36,518 --> 00:17:37,159
Empty of what?

163
00:17:37,538 --> 00:17:40,002
It's empty of whatever the heart, mind, thoughts,

164
00:17:39,982 --> 00:17:44,212
our psychophysical organism can produce.

165
00:17:44,333 --> 00:17:45,435
It's empty of that.

166
00:17:46,858 --> 00:17:55,900
And then later on, of course, the movement is towards, well, if there is this experience, what is it that experiences it?

167
00:17:55,880 --> 00:17:58,647
And that's where the Buddha himself wanted to keep off.

168
00:17:59,108 --> 00:18:07,393
Because once you start talking about an it that experiences, you're into the old terminology of soul, self, etc, etc.

169
00:18:07,613 --> 00:18:11,002
And he seems to be very shy of that.

170
00:18:10,982 --> 00:18:21,272
But of course, he does come close to it because he has to make some sort of declaration about Nibbana, about what that experience is.

171
00:18:21,894 --> 00:18:28,519
So every evening I say there is an unborn, an undying, an uncreated.

172
00:18:28,700 --> 00:18:33,724
And I'm using the word an in the Pali, it's just past tense.

173
00:18:34,226 --> 00:18:37,429
You know, there is unborn, undying Nibbana.

174
00:18:37,814 --> 00:18:38,976
and so on and so forth.

175
00:18:38,996 --> 00:18:40,979
You see, there's no a or the.

176
00:18:41,819 --> 00:18:43,301
So it leaves it very open.

177
00:18:43,843 --> 00:18:52,576
And then he says, if there were not this, there'd be no escape from birth and death and so on and so forth.

178
00:18:52,596 --> 00:19:03,432
So that's one of the very famous verses that come from what's known as a collection of his inspiring verses, the Udana Sutta.

179
00:19:04,577 --> 00:19:11,269
And the other one is the ayatana, which you can translate as a sort of dimension.

180
00:19:11,288 --> 00:19:17,500
So remember, the ayatana are your six sense bases and each base is discrete.

181
00:19:18,060 --> 00:19:19,763
It's separate from the other.

182
00:19:19,784 --> 00:19:23,589
You can't see through your nose, although people have tried.

183
00:19:24,592 --> 00:19:27,155
And they're completely separate from each other.

184
00:19:27,737 --> 00:19:30,602
And you can talk about them as a dimension.

185
00:19:30,952 --> 00:19:36,144
different dimensions of experience, different spheres of experience.

186
00:19:36,164 --> 00:19:45,486
So then he says that there is this sphere where none of this exists, where there's no coming, no going, no standing still, there's no time, there's no space, there's nothing.

187
00:19:46,007 --> 00:19:49,114
He's saying that just this is the end of suffering.

188
00:19:49,094 --> 00:20:02,511
So it's not as though he doesn't try to get across some idea of what Nirvana is, but he's very coy of turning it into a soul or a self or anything like that.

189
00:20:02,952 --> 00:20:07,058
And I think that was because of his time and place where the other sects were quite clear.

190
00:20:07,799 --> 00:20:16,131
The Jains, the Brahmins, all those were quite clear that there was this soul, an eternal soul.

191
00:20:20,144 --> 00:20:29,000
The Hindus now of course talk about I am that.

192
00:20:29,761 --> 00:20:30,663
I am that.

193
00:20:31,766 --> 00:20:37,175
So that's one way of neutralizing it without sort of creating too many concepts.

194
00:20:37,596 --> 00:20:38,198
I am that.

195
00:20:39,039 --> 00:20:39,299
Yeah.

196
00:20:42,065 --> 00:21:05,759
so those um that gives you i think some pointers hopefully um there is of course the lovely verses from we name we name was the sixth patriarch the sixth and patriarch he was a very poor fellow he ended up working in the kitchens and stuff and um the master was retiring and so uh

197
00:21:06,684 --> 00:21:19,922
He wanted somebody to take over the heir to his monastery, or to the tradition rather, the whole Zen tradition, or Chan, as they would call it.

198
00:21:19,942 --> 00:21:22,305
And so he asked people to write their understanding.

199
00:21:22,545 --> 00:21:28,913
Well, there was a sort of a monk within the monastery who was considered to be

200
00:21:29,163 --> 00:21:58,056
the successor by everybody and he wrote this verse he says uh the body is like the bodhi tree the heart is a mirror bright every day wipe it clean the mirror yeah so no dust may alight you see and when we name saw that he reckoned he hadn't quite got it so without um

201
00:21:58,153 --> 00:22:05,403
without putting his name to it, he wrote, there is no Bodhi tree and the heart has no stand.

202
00:22:06,525 --> 00:22:07,566
There's nothing whatsoever.

203
00:22:07,826 --> 00:22:08,907
Where can the dust alight?

204
00:22:10,028 --> 00:22:14,295
And the master then realized that he was, of course, the sixth patriarch.

205
00:22:14,755 --> 00:22:15,737
So he had to escape.

206
00:22:15,797 --> 00:22:22,305
He told him to go and hide himself because the other monks would have killed him, I think.

207
00:22:23,652 --> 00:22:27,698
So there you've got a materialist view, right?

